    <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*ā-dayana-</w></mentioned> от
            <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>dī</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="ira"
                ><w>day-</w><gloss><q>глядеть</q></gloss></mentioned>, („гляделка“); ср. <mentioned
            xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/><w>ādēn</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"
                ><w>ādēnk</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="pal"
            ><lang/><w>āδēnak</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="pal"><w>ādēng</w><note
                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="">
            ()</note></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
            ><lang/><w>āδēnak(''δ'yn'k)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                ><lang/><w>āyəna</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="kho"><w>ātīna</w></mentioned>,
        (ср. также <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
            ><lang/><w>dyāna</w><gloss><q>видимый</q></gloss></mentioned>), <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>āyīna</w></mentioned>. Звуковая история слова может быть уточнена
        привлечением таких случаев стяжения группы %iауа%i, как <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_fijjaw"/> ‘пастух’ из %ifæjau%i, fæstijæ ‘сзади’ из %ifæstæjæ%i,
        %izærdijæn%i ‘сердцу’ из %izærdæjæn%i, %iærtijæn%i ‘трем’ из %iærtæjæn%i и т. п.; по
        аналогии с этими случаями предполагаем: *%iādayana%i →*%iadæjæn%i → *%iadijæn%i → *%iadjæn%i
        → %iajdæn%i. Из *%iādaina%i (<bibl><author>Benveniste</author><ref target="#ref_BSL"
                /><biblScope>LII 9</biblScope></bibl>) имели бы *%iadīn%i, как из %iaxšaina%i- →
            <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æxsīn"/>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">It traces back to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"
            ><lang/><w>*ā-dayana-</w></mentioned> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"
            ><lang/><w>dī</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="ira"
                ><w>day-</w><gloss><q>look</q></gloss></mentioned>, (“looker”): <mentioned
            xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/><w>ādēn</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"
                ><w>ādēnk</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="pal"
            ><lang/><w>āδēnak</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="pal"><w>ādēng</w><note
                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="">
            ()</note></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
            ><lang/><w>āδēnak(ˈˈδ'ynyk)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                ><lang/><w>āyəna</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="kho"><w>ātīna</w></mentioned>,
        (cf. also <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
            ><lang/><w>dyāna</w><gloss><q>visible</q></gloss></mentioned>), <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>āyīna</w></mentioned>. The sound history of the word can be refined by
        invoking such cases of contraction of the %iaya%i group as <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_fijjaw"/> ‘shepherd’ from %ifæjau%i, %ifæstijæ%i ‘behind’ from
        %ifæstæjæ%i, %izærdijæn%i ‘heart (dat)’ from %izærdæjæn%i, %iærtijæn%i ‘three (dat)’ from
        %iærtæjæn%i and so on; by analogy with these cases, we assume: *%iādayana%i →*%iadæjæn%i →
        *%iadijæn%i → *%iadjæn%i → %iajdæn%i. From *%iādaina%i
                (<bibl><author>Benveniste</author><ref target="#ref_BSL"/><biblScope>LII
                9</biblScope></bibl>) we would have had *%iadīn%i, as from %iaxšaina%i- → <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_æxsīn"/>.</etym>
